#Text=Emily Stanley
#Text=Emily Stanley is an American professor of limnology at the University of Wisconsin – Madison .
#Text=She was named a 2018 Ecological Society of America Fellow and her research focuses on the ecology of freshwater ecosystems .
#Text=Early life and education
#Text=Emily Stanley was born in Bethlehem , Pennsylvania to parents Frank and Elizabeth .
#Text=She has three siblings : Jonathan , Elizabeth , and James .

#Text=Emily Stanley received her B.S. in Biology at Yale University in 1984 , her M.S. in Biology at Southwest Texas State University in 1986 , and her Ph.D. in Zoology at Arizona State University in 1993 . [ 1 ]
#Text=Her Ph.D. advisor was Stuart Fisher , a Professor Emeritus at the School of Life Sciences at Arizona State University . [ 2 ]
#Text=Career and research

#Text=After completing her Ph. D. , Stanley worked as a Post-Doctoral Research Assistant at the University of Alabama for two years , then was Associate Professor at Oklahoma State University in the zoology department for three years .
#Text=In 1998 she became associate professor at the University of Wisconsin Center for Limnology and Department of Integrative Biology .
#Text=In 2010 , she was promoted to Full Professor . [ 1 ]
#Text=Stanley 's research focuses on limnology , as well as river and stream ecosystem ecology .

#Text=Her Ph.D. thesis studied a stream in the Arizona Sonoran Desert to determine how the different parts of the streams dried during warmer months , and it was determined that when each part of the stream ecosystem shrinks and expands , the stream as a whole fluctuates in size . [ 3 ]

#Text=According to her paper , this research could help predict how drying patterns cause changes in ecosystems , and knowing that stream ecosystems change over space and time can also be used to predict how streams could change due to climate change . [ 3 ]
#Text=Other research of hers includes studying the effects of dam removal on ecosystems and predicting how best to manage the consequences . [ 4 ]
#Text=She has also researched how different factors such as hydrology , biochemistry , invasive species , and human land-use alter lakes and rivers .
#Text=Changes in freshwater ecosystems , according to her research , can affect services humans get from these ecosystems , such as drinking water . [ 5 ]
#Text=Emily Stanley has also studied riparian zones , which are the areas between rivers and land , and how human impacts can change these ecosystems . [ 6 ]
#Text=In addition , she has studied hyporheic zones , areas where surface water mixes with groundwater , and researched how water and nutrients are exchanged between the two . [ 7 ]
#Text=Awards and honors
#Text=2003-2005 – University of Wisconsin Vilas Associate Award [ 8 ]
#Text=2003-2008 – University of Wisconsin Vilas Associate Award [ 9 ]
#Text=2006 – Aldo Leopold Leadership Program [ 10 ]
#Text=2008 – University of Wisconsin Romnes Faculty Fellowship Award [ 11 ]
#Text=2015 – University of Wisconsin Kellett Mid-Career Faculty Researcher Award [ 12 ]
#Text=2018 – Fellow of the Society for Freshwater Science [ 13 ]
#Text=2018 – ASLO G. Evelyn Hutchinson Award [ 14 ]
#Text=2018 – Fellow of the Ecological Society of America [ 15 ]
#Text=Notable Publications
#Text=1997 : " Ecosystem expansion and contraction in streams , " BioScience [ 3 ]
#Text=1998 : " The functional significance of the hyporheic zone in streams and rivers , " Annual Review of Ecology and Systematics [ 7 ]
